Following the same settings in
Section V-D1,
we evaluate and compare the performance of
the proposed game-theoretic schemes against the baseline scheme
in terms of test accuracy at FL servers. In a uniform client distribution scenario, α=0.0𝛼0.0\alpha=0.0 and β=1.0𝛽1.0\beta=1.0, the baseline and game base models perform similar accuracy shown table I. FL servers achieved similar test accuracy in both models on 1 class label non-iid data distribution. The FL server’s test accuracy is also close enough on 2 class labels data distribution.
First, when α=0.0𝛼0.0\alpha=0.0 and β=1.0𝛽1.0\beta=1.0
(i.e., clients are uniformly distributed to edge servers),
the baseline and the game-theoretic schemes achieve similar test accuracy,
as shown in the last rows of
Tables I.
In the first experiment,
each client has training data with only 1 class label;
in another experiment,
each client has training data with 2 class labels.
Therefore, not all FL servers can obtain models
trained from the data with most class labels.
Particularly,
if an FL server acquires a small number of clients,
its model is trained based on the data with only a few class labels.
Also, since
clients are randomly selected from the client pool,
an FL server could receive a model updated based on the data with
different number of class labels
in different rounds.
Thus, testing accuracy varies in rounds,
even though they get model updates from the same number of clients.
As we can see, the baseline scheme does not assign bandwidth fairly.
For example, when α=0.4𝛼0.4\alpha=0.4 and β=0.6𝛽0.6\beta=0.6,
FL server S0subscript𝑆0S_{0} acquires less bandwidth than S4subscript𝑆4S_{4};
therefore, it has lower test accuracy than S4subscript𝑆4S_{4}.
In the game-theoretic schemes,
except for the highly heterogeneous scenarios such as when
(α=0.6,β=0.2formulae-sequence𝛼0.6𝛽0.2\alpha=0.6,\beta=0.2), (α=0.8,β=0.2formulae-sequence𝛼0.8𝛽0.2\alpha=0.8,\beta=0.2) and (α=0.8,β=0.4formulae-sequence𝛼0.8𝛽0.4\alpha=0.8,\beta=0.4),
we can see that FL servers
S0subscript𝑆0S_{0} and S4subscript𝑆4S_{4} have similar test accuracy and are better than baseline schema.

We evaluate the impact of fund heterogeneity.
Table II illustrates the test accuracy
as heterogeneity parameter γ𝛾\gamma varies. We can observe that an FL server achieves higher test accuracy when it has a larger fund. For example, in the distributed scheme and training data with 2 class labels, for γ=0.4𝛾0.4\gamma=0.4, FL server S0subscript𝑆0S_{0} has a fund of 0.5 and a test accuracy of 79.05%percent79.0579.05\%, whereas S4subscript𝑆4S_{4} has a larger fund of 1.0 and a higher test accuracy of 86.71%percent86.7186.71\%. Therefore, S4subscript𝑆4S_{4} acquired more bandwidth with the fund and achieved higher test accuracy.
